2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window between '2024-01-24 08:18:50' and '2024-01-24 08:48:50' UTC (inclusive). Keep the timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value.
3) Join the filtered rows with the computed P95 and P5 for their (cmdb_id, kpi_name).
4) Identify high anomalies: rows where value >= P95. For each high anomaly compute severity = value / P95. Return up to top 20 high-anomaly rows sorted by severity descending, with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p95, severity.
5) Identify low anomalies: rows where value <= P5. For each low anomaly compute severity_low = P5 / max(value, 1e-12). Return up to top 20 low-anomaly rows sorted by severity_low descending, with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p5, severity_low.
6) Return an aggregate table of anomaly counts per cmdb_id (count of high + low anomalies) sorted by count descending, limited to top 20 rows.
7) Also return the first 10 rows (head) of the filtered metric data within the incident window for quick inspection.
Limit outputs to the specified columns and row counts; do not print full series.
